title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We can look at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[2\times 2]]></fr:tex> matrices as acting on points <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x,y)\in \mathbb {R}^{2}]]></fr:tex> on the plane. We turn <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x,y)]]></fr:tex> into a column vector.</fr:p><fr:p>We have rotation anticlockwise by an angle <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\theta ]]></fr:tex> given by
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}_{\theta } = \begin {bmatrix}\cos (\theta ) & -\sin (\theta )\\ \sin (\theta ) & \cos (\theta )\end {bmatrix}.]]></fr:tex>
Reflection about the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>-axis is
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\mathbf {R}  =\begin {bmatrix}1 & 0\\0 & -1 \end {bmatrix}.]]></fr:tex>
Dilation by a positive real number <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda \gt  0]]></fr:tex> is a diagonal matrix
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[  \mathbf {D}_{\lambda } =\begin {bmatrix}\lambda  & 0\\   0 & \lambda    \end {bmatrix}.]]></fr:tex>
Observe for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0\lt \lambda \lt 1]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {D}_{\lambda }]]></fr:tex> be a contraction.</fr:p>
 
   
